abstract: U.S. President Donald Trump issued an expanded version of his travel ban on Friday that targets prospective immigrants from Nigeria and five other countries, a move that could affect thousands of people and reignite debate on whether the policy is discriminatory.
snippet: U.S. President Donald Trump issued an expanded version of his travel ban on Friday that targets prospective immigrants from Nigeria and five other countries, a move that could affect thousands of people and reignite debate on whether the policy is...
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — U.S. President Donald Trump issued an expanded version of his travel ban on Friday that targets prospective immigrants from Nigeria and five other countries, a move that could affect thousands of people and reignite debate on whether the policy is discriminatory.
headline_main: Trump's Expanded Travel Ban Targets Nigeria, Five Other Countries
headline_print_headline: Trump's Expanded Travel Ban Targets Nigeria, Five Other Countries

abstract: Multiple Democratic candidates said they expected to finish strong in the caucuses, though official results appeared to be a ways off.
snippet: Multiple Democratic candidates said they expected to finish strong in the caucuses, though official results appeared to be a ways off.
lead_paragraph: Troy Price, the chairman of the Iowa Democratic Party, said shortly after 1 a.m. that he expected to have caucus results to report “later today” after party officials had manually tallied the data.

abstract: There were more pressing matters at hand Sunday than the president’s 2020 election opponents, including the coronavirus and his State of the Union address on Tuesday, but he made little mention of them.
snippet: There were more pressing matters at hand Sunday than the president’s 2020 election opponents, including the coronavirus and his State of the Union address on Tuesday, but he made little mention of them.
lead_paragraph: On many levels, President Trump’s weekend — full of golf, catered salmon and plenty of patriotic-themed evening wear — could have been devised to offer relief and a sense of triumph to a president who spent the first month of an election year watching from the sidelines as the Senate debated his future.
